Rating: 3
This real value in this recipe is in the *method* moreso than the seasonings. I used my "standard" fried chicken seasoning formula for the flour (a mixture of 1 Tbls. poultry seasoning, 1 tsp. pepper, 1 1/2 tsp. paprika, 1/2 tsp. onion powder, 1/4 tsp. garlic powder, and 1 1/2 tsp. MSG ["Accent"]). You must go HEAVY on the seasonings, because flour is bland - just like with "conventional" fried chicken. The reviewer who mentioned the importance of using a pan large enough to allow some space between the pieces of chicken to insure crispiness is correct. I used a sheet pan (which has low sides) and I think that also contributes to crisp skin (better heat circulation around each piece). If your oven isn't perfectly level (you'll notice this when melting the butter if the butter pools in one area of the pan), then rotate the pan 180 degrees halfway through the baking time when the chicken is skinside down, and halfway through when the chicken is skinside up. The chicken was tender, juicy, flavorful, and crispy - and the gravy was delicious, too!

